Customer Clustering

Using simulated data, I plan to use K-means and agglomerative clustering to create groups of customers. This clustering could in turn be used for targeting ads or timing sales for specific populations to maximize profits.

The data

The dataset that I am using can be downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rodsaldanha/arketing-campaign/data. It was created by Rodolfo Saldanha.

The dataset contains 29 columns and 2239 rows. The columns include information about the customers who have shopped at a specific store. Each row represents a customer. The dataset was intended to be used as a marketing tool to see which groups of customers respond to various marketing campaigns. I will not be taking the marketing campaigns into account, as I am just interested in learning about how I can cluster the customers together into various groups.

I will be cleaning the data by removing all rows with null values. I will also be removing any unneeded columns.

In[8]:
df.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)

Now I will create a few new columns.

Childreninhousehold will combine Kidhome and Teenhome to get the total number of children in the home.

Parent will be a boolean 1 if the individual has kids or 0 if not.

Age will replace Year_Birth.

Total_spent will add up all of the customer's spending in the various categories provided.

In[9]:
df['Childreninhousehold'] = df['Kidhome'] + df['Teenhome']

df['Parent'] = np.where(df.Childreninhousehold> 0, 1, 0)

df['Age'] = 2024 - df['Year_Birth']
df['Total_spent'] = df['MntWines'] + df['MntFruits'] + df['MntMeatProducts'] + df['MntFishProducts'] + df['MntGoldProds']

Modeling the Data

First I will model the data using K-means clustering. Using the elbow method to find the optimal value for k

In[15]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(df)
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(df),columns= df.columns )

scaled_df.dropna(inplace=True)
In[16]:
Sum_of_squared_distances = []
K = range(1,15)
for k in K:
    km = KMeans(init="k-means++", n_clusters=k)
    km = km.fit(df)
    Sum_of_squared_distances.append(km.inertia_)

ax = sns.lineplot(x=K, y=Sum_of_squared_distances)
ax.lines[0].set_linestyle("--")

# Add a vertical line to show the optimum number of clusters
plt.axvline(4, color='#F26457', linestyle=':')

plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Distances')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()
In[17]:
pca = PCA(4)
transformed_df = pca.fit_transform(scaled_df)
k = 4
km = KMeans(init="k-means++", n_clusters=k, max_iter=100, n_init=1)
labels = km.fit_predict(transformed_df)

        silhouette_score(X_principal, ac6.fit_predict(X_principal)))

plt.xlabel('Number of clusters') 
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score') 
plt.show()

Based on the silouhette scores, the optimal number of clusters is 4.

Conclusion

Both k-means and agglomerative clustering were effective in creating clusters with this dataset. It is clear that the agglomerative model weighed income very heavily as there is a clear divide in income groups between the 6 clusters. I found the K-means model to be far more interesting as it appeared to group customers not only by their income, but also emphasized whether or not the customer was a parent and how many children they have. Going forward, we could look at spending habits of each of these groups and use that to target advertisements tailored to each specific group.
